TL;DR:A new study from @EnvDefenseFund scientists examines contributions of greenhouse gas emissions from economic sectors to future warming, & finds that standard metrics CUT IN HALF the role of #methane dominated industries in the coming decades.https://t.co/amgQuhqFpx

Here are 3 ways to IMPROVE stats and decisions:1. Never rely exclusively on CO2e; use multiple metrics/models.2. Report underlying data by individual greenhouse gas.3. Be explicit about metric/time horizon underlying GHG statistics.

It is well-known among the scientific community that CO2e does a poor job conveying warming impacts over multiple timescales. https://t.co/1LzaDTTJp3But there is no one-size-fits-all solution to replace it, so CO2e persists.So what CAN be done?

This distortion can lead to suboptimal policies & efforts to curb climate change.Our new paper shows just how badly this distortion can warp the focus of #climateaction, obscuring problem areas & masking the benefit of important #cutmethane solutions.https://t.co/DIZSFI1ufA

The climate model shows that sectors dominated by #methane emissions could cause HALF of additional GHG-induced warming by 2050. But the CO2e metric implies they only cause one quarter!So CO2e CUTS IN HALF methane‚Äôs importance in the coming decades.@MethaneHub @MethaneData

This is clear when using a simple, more accurate #climatemodel to do the physics and comparing to what you get from using the standard CO2e metric (based on GWP100).CO2e drastically DISTORTS how sectors contribute to warming in the coming decades - especially #methane.

So what does this mean for assessing contributions of economic sectors to future GHG-induced warming?In the coming decades, methane-dominated sectors (#agriculture, fossil fuel prod & dist, waste) contribute TWO TIMES MORE to warming (& #mitigation!) than typically recognized. https://t.co/niRQ1tEdCy

Bottom line‚Ä¶ CO2e, which is baked into the #climatepolicy dialogue DOES NOT convey what will happen in the near-term. It isn‚Äôt designed to, but most don‚Äôt even realize that there is a timescale associated with these calculations.

The standard CO2e metric therefore spreads out methane‚Äôs warming effect over a 100 yr period.This MASKS methane‚Äôs strong warming impact when it is actually warming the atmosphere.And DEEMPHASIZES methane‚Äôs role in contributing to and mitigating(!) the #climatecrisis.

Several GHGs, like #methane, only last in the atmosphere for decades at most. So their warming impact relatively short-lived.But the CO2e metric calculates their warming effect for 100 yrs‚Ä¶ including DECADES when they're no longer warming the climate.https://t.co/wRiuMngvRV

CO2e calculates the amount of CO2 that would cause the same warming over the following 100yrs as the emissions of a non-CO2 gas.A 100yr timescale makes sense for CO2, bc it can last (& warm the planet) for centuries.But not all gases are created equal.https://t.co/jZQsd7Zn3G

The climate crisis is a crisis of human emotion. Whilst sharing knowledge about why climates are changing and what we can do to mitigate biodiversity collapse is essential, equally essential is recognising ‚Äì and supporting - emotional resilience and empowerment. They matter.

It's an exploration of what it means to be human; of what lies ahead on this rapidly changing planet and of what impacts our actions can & will have on the potential extinction of life on earth. It's therefore not something to address in the same way as, say, teaching algebra...

So, living on a spherical planet üåçmeans that species are unlikely to respond linearly to climate warming, even in the absence of all the interesting biology that we know can lead to abrupt collapses of populations and ecosystems
The greater availability of warm climates also means that most populations within a species' range are skewed towards similarly warm conditions

Because of the Earth's shape, warm climates are more widespread. Area declines with latitude and altitude üóªand in the tropics the latitudinal temperature gradient is relatively flatThese properties are probably one reason warm environments contain more species. https://t.co/qsNS53lJRl

But why then are populations clustered in thermal niche space? There could be several reasons but we think that this clustering, and therefore abrupt thermal exposure, may be the outcome of living on a round, rotating planet üåç, 'an apple whirling silently in space'

It's like standing on a beach watching the tide come in. Initially the sea doesn't advance much because there is a steep bank. But then, as the water rises, and where the beach flattens off, the sea suddenly comes rushing in.

We found that populations within a species are not uniformly distributed across its thermal niche - most populations live under similar conditions. As the climate warms, these populations will all pass the species' thermal limit at a similar time in the future https://t.co/3QFukfOXhm

Our expectation was that with a roughly linear rate of warming projected this century (notwithstanding substantial short term variability) the thermal exposure of a species' geographic range would also expand approx linearlyThis doesn't seem to be the case. Why? ü§î
This is all deeply concerning stuff, but there is also some interesting science üß™in here to keep us going.....

Abrupt and widespread climate driven losses of species is already happening and with continued warming üìàthe number of species at risk of passing thermal thresholds increases.
